    <p>
      <strong>Summary</strong>
    </p>
    <p xmlns="">
      "Eddings' BELGARIAD is exactly the kind of fantasy I like.
    It has magic, adventure, humor, mystery, and a certain
    delightful human insight."
      <br />
      Piers Anthony
      <br />
      Long ago, the Storyteller claimed, in this first book of THE
    BELGARIAD, the evil god Torak drove men and Gods to war. But
    Belgarath the Sorcerer led men to reclaim the Orb that
    protected men of the West. So long as it lay at Riva, the
    prophecy went, men would be safe.
      <br />
      But Garion did not believe in such stories. Brought up on a
    quiet farm by his Aunt Pol, how could he know that the Apostate
    planned to wake dread Torak, or that he would be led on a quest
    of unparalleled magic and danger by those he loved--but did not
    know...?
    </p>
